icus 1.153 ὀμνύντες is restored for the uncertain form ὀμοῦντες)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>future</i> ὀμοῦμαι, εῖ, εῖται, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.233, 9.274, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 194, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 246, “Lys.” 193, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 1.3.11, etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Doric dialect</i> <i>1st pers.</i> <i>plural</i> ὀμιώμεθα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Lysistrata” 183 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; later <i>future</i> ὀμόσω [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Anthologia Graeca” 12.201 (2nd c.AD: Strato Epigrammaticus), 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Cicero” 23, etc.\">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ὤμοσα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 4.253, etc. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; <i>Epic dialect</i> ὤμοσσα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 20.313; _Epic dialect_ also without augment ὄμοσα, -οσσα, 19.113, 10.328 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> ὀμώμοκα [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hippolytus” 612, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 1471, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>pluperfect</i> ὠμωμόκειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 5.1.35, 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 9.16, 19.318 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>middle</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Pausanias Periegeta 10.26.3 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>], <i>aorist</i> <i>participle</i> ὀμοσάμενος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “SIG” 531.28 (Dyme, 3rd c.BC), “IG” 5(2).357.11 (from Stymphalus), also in compounds ἀντ-, ἀπ-, δι-, ὑπ-\">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, <i>future</i> ὀμοσθήσομαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 3.34 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>aorist</i> ὠμόσθην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 7.4.10, (ὑπ-) 4th c.BC: Hyperides Orator “Fragmenta” 202; but ὠμόθην 4th c.BC: Isaeus Orator 2.40, (ὑπ-) 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 48.25 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>perfect</i> <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>singular</i> ὀμώμοται [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1284, ὀμώμοσται 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rhesus” 816, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1377a11 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>3rd.pers.</i> <i>plural</i> ὀμώμονται Legal cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.98 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <i>participle</i> ὀμωμοσμένος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 7.10, 22.4, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1377b7 (ὠμοσμένος see reading in 2nd c.AD: Appianus Historicus “Αιβυκή” 83, etc.)\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]:—<b>swear,</b> with <i>accusative</i> <i>cognate</i>, ὀμνυέτω δέ τοι ὅρκον [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.175, +others; ὅτις κ᾽ ἐπίορκον ὀμόσσῃ 3.279; ἑκὼν ἐπίορκον ὀμόσσας 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 282: with _dative_ _person_, νῦν μοι ὄμοσσον.. ὅρκον 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.108, +others; πρός τινα 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 14.331, 19.288 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]:—<i>passive</i>, ὀμώμοται γὰρ ὅοκος ἐκ θεῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Agamemnon” 1284; ὅρκων ὀμωμος μένων 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 7.10; εἰ ὀμώμοσται οὗτος [ὁ ὅρκος] 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1377a11, compare b7. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>swear to</b> a thing, <b>affirm</b> or <b>confirm by oath,</b> <br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> followed by <i>accusative</i>, ταῦτα δ᾽ ἐγὼν ἐθέλω ὀμόσαι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 19.187, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1145, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Agesilaus” 1.11 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὄ. τὰς σπονδάς Foed. cited in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.47; τὴν εἰρήνην 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.32, compare 9.16; θεῶν πίστεις τινί 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.30, etc. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> followed by <i>future</i> <i>infinitive</i>, <b>swear that one will..,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 21.373, etc., compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 623, 941 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] (<i>present</i> <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.188 codices): frequently with ἦ μέν, _Attic dialect_ ἦ μήν,\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] preceding the <i>infinitive</i>, καί μοι ὄμοσσον ἦ μέν μοι.. ἀρήξειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.76, compare 10.321, 5th c.BC: Lysias Orator 31.1, 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Historia Graeca (Hellenica)” 5.3.26, etc.: also by \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<i>aorist</i> <i>infinitive</i> and ἄν, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “An.” 7.7.40 \">Refs</a>]: by <i>present</i> <i>infinitive</i>, <b>swear that one does..,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 357 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: by <i>perfect</i> <i>infinitive</i>, <b>swear that one has..,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.119; ὤμνυς μὴ γεγονέναι 5th c.BC: Magnes Comicus 6 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: by <i>aorist</i> <i>infinitive</i>, <b>swear that one did..,</b> ὀμνύουσι μὴ 'κπιεῖν ἀλλ᾽ ἢ μίαν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pherecrates Comicus 143.9, compare 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 2.179 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>](<i>aorist</i> <i>infinitive</i> is perhaps used, without ἄν, in <i>future</i> sense, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 23.170 (assuming variant))\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]: sometimes a clause follows in the <i>indicative</i>, ὀμνύω.., ἦ μὴν ἐγὼ ἐθυόμην [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 6.1.31; ὄμνυμί σοι.., οὐκ ἤθελον.. 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus “Adon.” 22. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.3</b></Level3> <i>absolutely</i>, εἶπον ὀμόσας ἄν I would have <b>given my word of honour,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Symposium” 215d. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> with <i>accusative</i> of the person or thing sworn by, <b>swear by,</b> νῦν μοι ὄμοσσον ἀάατον Στυγὸς ὕδωρ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 14.271; γαιήοχον ἐννοσίγαιον ὄμνυθι 23.585, compare 15.40, 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 5.7, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 529, 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1185, etc.; ὀμωμοκὼς τοὺς θεούς 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 18.217 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὄμνυμι θεοὺς καὶ θεάς followed by <i>infinitive</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Anabasis” 6.6.17, compare 6.1.31: rarely with _dative_, τῷ γὰρ ὄμνυτ᾽\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἢ σιδαρέοισ; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 248: in Prose also with Preps., ὀ. καθ᾽ ἱερῶν τελείων Legal cited in 5th-6th c.BC: Andocides Orator 1.97, 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 5.47; κατ᾽ ἐξωλείας 4th c.BC: Demosthenes Orator 21.119; κατὰ τῆς Πολιάδος 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Symp.” 32; εἰς τὸν Οὐιτέλλιον 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Otho” 18; ἐπὶ τῶν ἱερῶν 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 38.20.5; ἐν Κυρίῳ LXX.Judg.21.7; ἐν τῷ ναῷ NT.Matt.23.16:—\">NT+5th c.BC+</a>]<i>passive</i>, ὀμώμοσται Ζεύς Zeus <b>has been sworn by, adjured,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Rhesus” 816, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 1241. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G3660","accentedUnicode":"ὄμνυμι","shortDef":"to declare an oath, swear an oath, promise with an oath","mediumDef":"to declare an oath, swear an oath, promise with an oath <br /><b>to swear,</b> <ref='Mat.5.34'>Mt. 5:34</ref>; <b>to promise with an oath,</b> <ref='Mrk.6.23'>Mk. 6:23</ref>; <ref='Act.2.30'>Acts 2:30;</ref> 7:17","stepGloss":"to swear","stepTransliteration":"omnumi","count":26,"_es_Definition":"jurar, prometer bajo juramento","_zh_tw_Definition":"(對神明) 起誓, 立誓 (以表若不屬實將得報應)","_zh_Definition":"(对神明) 起誓, 立誓 (以表若不属实将得报应)","_step_Type":"verb","_vi_Definition":"thề","_zh_tw_Gloss":"起誓","_es_Gloss":"jurar","_zh_Gloss":"起誓"}]}